. The Starting Point: 
The MLP Failure:
I began by attempting to fit a Multi-Layer Perception (MLP) to the raw UCI data. My goal was to see if a Neural Network could find a universal "Parkinson’s Voice."
The Reality: The MLP failed to generalize. It produced negative $R^2$ values for specific demographics, particularly the younger outliers.
My Diagnosis: I realized the MLP was struggling because the data isn't a smooth gradient; it has massive "jumps" between a 36-year-old and a 70-year-old that a standard feed-forward network couldn't bridge without a subject-aware baseline.
2. The "Fake" Success: The 0.99 Random ForestI switched to a Random Forest to handle the non-linear gaps. Instantly, the $R^2$ jumped to 0.99.
The Catch: Instead of accepting this "win," I audited the Feature Importance. I found that Age and Sex were doing 90% of the work.
My Discovery: The model wasn't practicing medicine; it was practicing Identity Recognition. It used the unique age of the 36-year-old female as a "Subject ID" to memorize her UPDRS score. I called this out as Identity Leakage.
3. The Stress Test: Going "Age-Blind"To find the actual signal, I stripped away Age and Sex and forced the model to look only at Acoustic Features (Jitter, Shimmer, HNR, DFA).The Crash: The $R^2$ for the 36-year-old female dropped to -26.8.
The Truth: This proved that the voice features alone are "noisy." Without knowing the patient's age, the model couldn't tell the difference between a shaky young voice and a normal old voice.
4. The Scientific Fix: Cleaning the CohortI realized the dataset had "Bookend Outliers" (Age 36 and 85) that were confusing the logic. I removed them to focus on the core clinical group (49–74). I also moved to Gender-Specific Bins to account for biological differences in vocal folds.
The Result: I found a legitimate, honest signal in Females aged 56–63 ($R^2 = 0.54$). This is the only part of the data where the voice features actually correlate with the disease without "cheating" through age.

⚠️ The Critical Flaws I Identified in the Dataset
Identity Leakage: The unique ages act as proxies for individual subjects, making "Global" models appear more accurate than they actually are.
Lack of Control Group: There are no healthy 70-year-olds in this set. This forces the model to assume that "Old Voice = Parkinson's Voice," which is a dangerous clinical fallacy.
The "Excel Child" Theory: The features are Global Averages of 30-second clips. One cough or throat-clear ruins the entire row of data.
Ambiguous Timing: test_time is just a counter of days in the study; it doesn't tell us when the disease started or the time since the last medication dose (ON/OFF state).

